#### Required Insurance

**General Liability Insurance:**
Per [Insureon](https://www.insureon.com/small-business-insurance/general-liability/cost):
- Small businesses pay **$42/month average** ($500/year)
- Coverage: $1M per occurrence / $2M aggregate (standard)
- Protects against: Property damage, bodily injury, advertising injury

**Professional Liability (E&O):**
Per [Progressive](https://www.progressivecommercial.com/business-insurance/professional-liability-insurance/professional-liability-insurance-cost/):
- Median cost: **$42/month** ($500/year)
- Protects against: Claims of negligence, mistakes, bad advice

**Recommended Coverage:**
| Coverage Type | Annual Cost | Why Needed |
|---------------|-------------|------------|
| General Liability | $500-800 | Home visits, golf courses |
| Professional Liability | $500-800 | Tech support errors |
| **Total** | **$1,000-1,600/year** | Required for credibility |

> Source: [Simply Business](https://www.simplybusiness.com/business-insurance/general-liability-insurance/cost/), [The Hartford](https://www.thehartford.com/general-liability-insurance/how-much-does-general-liability-cost)

#### Liability Waivers

Per [TermsFeed](https://www.termsfeed.com/blog/liability-waiver/) and [WaiverSign](https://www.waiversign.com/blog/what-to-include-liability-waiver), valid waivers require:

**Essential Components:**
1. Participant identification (full name, contact)
2. Company identification
3. Clear description of activity/service
4. Acknowledgment and assumption of risk
5. Release of liability (clear language)
6. Covenant not to sue
7. Severability clause
8. Governing law provision
9. Voluntary signature with date

**Waiver Limitations:**
- Cannot protect against gross negligence
- Cannot protect against intentional harm
- Must follow state-specific laws
- Courts scrutinize waivers carefully

**Recommendation:** Use digital waivers via WaiverSign or HelloSign for easy collection.

#### Independent Contractor Agreements

**Must Include:**
- Clear IC status language
- Scope of services
- Payment terms
- No benefits provision
- Own tools/equipment
- Ability to work elsewhere
- Termination terms
- Confidentiality (for tech support)
- Non-compete (if applicable)
- Insurance requirements

**California Consideration:**
AB5 law requires careful classification. Ensure contractors:
- Control their own schedule
- Provide services to multiple clients
- Have their own business entity (preferred)
- Set their own rates

